David Cameron will pay a historic visit to Burma this week – the first by a Western leader since decades of military rule ended last year.

The Prime Minister will signal Britain’s support for the political thaw in the former colony by meeting with Nobel Prize winner and opposition leader Aung San Suu Kyi, 66.

Miss Suu Kyi, who spent 15 of the past 22 years locked up by the former junta, won a seat in parliament for the first time in by-elections a week ago, seen by the Foreign Office as a step in the right direction for the repressive regime.

